posts.com: However, by the end of the 2nd season of TNG, this uniform began to be phased out, replaced with a similar but subtly different design. While the look and placement of the colors were similar, this new Star Trek uniform got rid of the piping on the shoulders, added a collar around the neck, and most importantly, changed the one-piece jumpsuit to a two-piece jacket and pants combination. Although the jumpsuit style continued to be worn by background actors and some of the women in the main cast, it was mostly phased out going into the 3rd season, and the new design became the standard uniform worn by the cast for the remainder of the show.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>178575263
The changes to the uniform design occurred because of some important behind-the-scenes reasons having to do with the comfort of the actors. While the idea of a uniform that did not wrinkle was an interesting one, the foot strap on the original uniforms pulled the jumpsuit so tight that it caused several actors, including Brent Spiner, Jonathan Frakes, and Patrick Stewart, significant back problems. The issues were so bad that Stewart's chiropractor reportedly told him he should sue the production for the damage done to his back. The original uniform was also made of a material that was reportedly not very breathable, causing actors to overheat under the studio lights and some not insignificant issues with body odor. When the uniforms were redesigned by new costume designer Robert Blackman, the material was changed to eliminate the odor issues and the switch to a two-piece suit put much less strain on the actors' backs.

It's funny how every time an anon brings this up 40kfags offer some dogshit book or Vidya plot that proves your point but they're so stupid they don't understand that.

40k is a genuinely dumb setting where nothing makes sense, which is absolutely fine because it started as a lame "parody" setting created by bong nerds using bong humour and eventually mutated into a popular war game where little thought was put into making the setting logical or even believable. All that mattered was making it look cool so nerds would buy .03 cents worth of plastic for $40 dollars, and here Games workshop succeeded. A lot of 40k stuff does look cool, in picture and on the table top. It would not look cool in motion, as video games and the Space Marine fan films have proven. In fact, once our in motion a lot of 40k stuff looks like pure unfiltered cringe, like Space Marines with their bloated outdated design that makes their occupant look like a toddler shoved in an iron man suit when they go helmetless.

So right out of the gate more than half the stuff in 40k.cant be used in a successful movie/show because it looks laughably dumb and will make everyone but hardcore fans laugh. Add in that there's no good storytelling or believable world building and you have all the pieces for a disaster in the making, like the Warcraft 2016 live action movie. The only possible way for it to be a success would be to utterly ignore all current world building, use an original story, and leave out almost everything from 40k outside of what looks good in motion like Cadia Pattern guardsmen or Sisters of Battle without their backpacks. If the movie/show is even 10% faithful to the setting it'll be a flop and one of the cringiest things ever filmed.

>>178571040
Yeah, I tend to agree. Leaving Channel Awesome cost him some viewers who were big fans of Doug, but mostly it completely removed him from the circle of online friends he had.
The biggest problem with Change the Channel is that it only sought to tear down Channel Awesome. It never set out to create anything new, to establish a new alternative to Channel Awesome. Everyone involved with Change the Channel just sought to milk shitting on Doug for as many views and patrons as they could get. But without creating something new, those views and patrons would prove to be temporary. Fans didn't stick around because there was nothing to stick around for.
Had they been smart, they would have established a new clique of reviewers. Channel Awesome, but done "right." They could have been cross promoting one another and working to build a new online community from the ashes of the old by pooling the reviewers and their fans together.
But by purely focusing on their own self-interests, they wound up fucking themselves over. The only one with any success is Lindsay Ellis, but she established herself before Change the Channel and took a very minor role in it.
I think the only guy who attempted to bring people together in the wake of Change the Channel was Linkara, and that was to do A Voice from the Dark, a radio play that's a sequel to all the anniversary movies (plus the Linkara movie since that's also within the Channel Awesome continuity). While not everyone from Change the Channel played along (including Allison Pregler, who was one of the driving forces behind Change the Channel and also got Lewis to cut ties with Brad Jones), Linkara managed to bring back a lot of retired reviewers, and the whole thing is definitely a fun project like those old anniversary films. But after that, everyone scattered back to the winds and faded into obscurity.

Channel Awesome was a product of its time, and it worked because the internet was less centralized. If you look at internet traffic from back in the day, it was spread out across a lot of different websites. Now Google owns like 90% of internet traffic. It's a part of the reason Channel Awesome fell apart in the first place, because it was an idea that was past its time.
So no, a Channel Awesome clone wouldn't have succeeded (Chez Apocalypse, Lindsay Ellis's effort at cloning Channel Awesome using her clique of internet friends, is proof of that). But they would have been smart to stay together as a group, set up a Discord or something, and continued to promote each other and work with one another. Keeping the community going would have benefited all of them.

everyone is given a helmet that blocks their vision but contains a radar interface that displays nearby sounds visually. players must use this display to navigate. they can briefly see the wall layout via echolocation by shouting or clapping. other players are invisible unless they're making a sound or their helmets are 'active', in which case they will ping their location every 6 seconds.
there are 16 players, half of them have 'active' helmets and the other half are 'inactive'. at the start they are told which one they are. when the time runs out all 'active' players are killed.
to become 'inactive' an 'active' player must touch a sensor on the back of an 'inactive' player's helmet, swapping their statuses. there is no indication for either player when this happens, and there is no way to know your own status once the game has started.

It's just sort of a Japanese flavored version of that kind of "lost in a magical world" story, but as far as I can tell it's not even really interested in showing us classic Japanese mythology as much as it's interested in this masturbatory show off of the studio's powers of imagination. Which isn't actually that interesting, because there is hardly any depth to their ideas. It's mostly just shitty OCs.

Pom Poko is a much better similar work which actually gets into proper Japanese folklore and spirituality a bit, and has something interesting going on for adults in the audience.

SpaceJam is a nightmare at WB for a lot of reasons. After "Who Framed Roger Rabbit" WB saw an opportunity to get their characters back in the spotlight. They dragged ass and couldn't get any projects going, mean while Disney had Ducktales and Chip N Dale and of course, Roger Rabbit himself.

Space Jam's development goes so far back that Mickey was supposed to cameo in it as a returned favor for Bugs and WB characters in Roger Rabbit, Disney got out of the cameo. WB just never knew what to do with these characters. They couldn't do a roger rabbit movie, so cramming them with a sports star was this marketing compromise. And from there it became a marketing driven project and no one ever knew how to handle it. It was a decent hit, especially as far as merchandise and rekindling the brand went. So ... sequel, yea? Baseball? A racing movie? A Spy movie? A lot of people at WB hated the project because it was just so corporate, way too corporate. They wanted to use the characters away from that framing. Eventually they caved and made a sequel, but damn if that ever just needed to not happen too.
